  <h3>The Colorado Springs Climate Challenge — and Opportunity</h3>
  <p>Colorado Springs has a semi-arid climate with only 13–16 inches of annual precipitation, hot dry summers, unpredictable Front Range hailstorms, and winters that can swing from 60°F to blizzard in the same week. This creates a compressed working season of roughly <strong>March through November</strong> for most services.</p>

  <p>This is both the market's biggest constraint and its biggest opportunity. Homeowners here genuinely need help more than in wetter climates — compact soil, dry conditions, and altitude create lawn care challenges most DIYers can't solve well. Professionals who understand local conditions command real loyalty.</p>

  <div class="callout-green">
    <p><strong>Water Efficiency = Growing Niche:</strong> Colorado Springs receives about 16 inches of annual precipitation. Colorado Springs Utilities offers a $1/sq ft rebate for qualifying xeriscape and drought-tolerant installations. Landscapers who position as water-efficiency specialists capture a segment their generalist competitors can't touch.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Key Demand Drivers Specific to Colorado Springs</h3>
  <ul class="checklist">
    <li>Military community (Fort Carson, Peterson AFB, Schriever) creates high turnover of homeowners needing immediate landscaping help</li>
    <li>Retirees in established neighborhoods (Broadmoor, Old North End, Briargate) seeking reliable, trustworthy help — the core Rent a Grandson demographic</li>
    <li>New suburban development to the north and east (Banning Lewis Ranch, Lorson Ranch) = first-time landscaping clients</li>
    <li>HOA communities with maintenance standards drive predictable recurring demand</li>
    <li>Water restriction compliance is increasingly essential — professional installation and smart irrigation are growing categories</li>
  </ul>
</div>
